CARTSI.title: Chicago Fed Advance Retail Trade Summary Weekly Index of Retail Trade
CARTSI.notes:
As described in Introducing CARTS: A New Index Tracking National Retail Spending (https://www.chicagofed.org/publications/blogs/chicago-fed-insights/2021/introducing-carts), The Chicago Fed Advance Retail Trade Summary (CARTS) refers to a weekly index of national retail spending that tracks the U.S. Census Bureau's Monthly Retail Trade Survey (MRTS) using a mixed-frequency dynamic factor model to combine high-frequency time series from five private companies (Consumer Edge, Facteus, Morning Consult, SafeGraph, and Womply), as well as two federal agencies (the U.S. Energy Information Administration and the U.S. Census Bureau).

The first release of the month covers the entirety of the previous month (final release), and the second release covers the first half of the current month (preliminary release). All weekly data are adjusted such that each month has four weeks, running from the 1st through 7th, 8th through 14th, 15th through 21st, and 22nd through the final day of the month. Additional information is available online (https://www.chicagofed.org/carts).

The CARTS weekly index series measures retail trade in millions of dollars.

For technical details, see:

Brave, Scott A., Michael Fogarty, Daniel Aaronson, Ezra Karger, and Spencer Krane, 2021, Tracking U.S. consumers in real time with a new weekly index of retail trade (https://www.chicagofed.org/~/media/publications/working-papers/2021/wp2021-05-pdf.pdf), Working Paper 2021-05, Federal Reserve Bank of Chicago. Crossref, https://doi.org/10.21033/wp-2021-052

CMRMT.title: Real Manufacturing and Trade Industries Sales
CMRMT.notes:
BEA Account Code: KPMT
Real Manufacturing and Trade Industries Sales is used in the calculation of CMRMTSPL (https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/CMRMTSPL). This series is based on the North American Industry Classification System (NAICS), which replaced the Standard Industrial Classification (SIC) system. The SIC is no longer published with this release, and the SIC series is HMRMT (https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/HMRMT).

CMRMTSPL.title: Real Manufacturing and Trade Industries Sales
CMRMTSPL.notes:
Real Manufacturing and Trade Industries Sales (CMRMTSPL) was first constructed by the Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis in June 2013. It is calculated using Real Manufacturing and Trade Industries Sales (HMRMT) (https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/HMRMT) and Real Manufacturing and Trade Industries (CMRMT) (https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/CMRMT).

Before January 1997
lag1(HMRMT) = one observation earlier than current time period observation
HMRMT_PC = the growth rate of HMRMT
lead1(CMRMTSPL) = one observation later than current time period observation
HMRMT_PC = [HMRMT/lag1(HMRMT) –1]
CMRMTSPL= lead1(CMRMTSPL)/(1+HMRMT_PC)

After December 1996
CMRMTSPL= CMRMT

RETAILIRNSA.title: Retailers: Inventories to Sales Ratio
RETAILIRNSA.notes: The inventories to sales ratios show the relationship of the end-of-month values of inventory to the monthly sales. These ratios can be looked at as indications of the number of months of inventory that are on hand in relation to the sales for a month. For example, a ratio of 2.5 would indicate that the retail stores have enough merchandise on hand to cover two and a half months of sales.
